\begin_layout Subsection
Uncertainty with perfect agency
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In reality however, 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is never observed.
 The level of severity for the patients a random variable represented by
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, characterized by a subjective density function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(s,\theta)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is a realization of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 with support in 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is a parameter that describes the uncertainty about 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

's corresponds to more uncertainty about 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the extreme case where the agent has no clue about 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is a uniform distribution
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The expected value of choosing an admissible treatment intensity
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(t,\theta)=E[u(t,s)]=\max_{t}\int_{a}^{b}u(t,s)f(s,\theta)ds\label{eq:expected-utility-prior}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is however possible to acquire costly information about 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 through medical diagnostics and physician effort.
 However, for information to be a desirable good we must have that more
 information makes the patient better off.
 As it it not possible to know the result of the information before it is
 obtained it is not exactly clear that more information is always better
 than less.
 For example, a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

surprising
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 observation will increase, rather than decrease, the uncertainty about
 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore we need a way to order information.
 Assume that for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in[0,\infty]$
\end_inset

 there is a potentially observable random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 which is correlated with 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 such that for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma<\gamma'$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}$
\end_inset

 is sufficient for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}'$
\end_inset

 as defined by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Blackwell1953"

\end_inset

.
 Then it is possible to interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 as a measure of the amount of information conveyed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}$
\end_inset

, such that smaller 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

's indicate more informative.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:sufficiency"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x\mid d,\gamma)$
\end_inset

 be the likelihood function.
 An observation of the random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}$
\end_inset

 is sufficient for all observation of the random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}'$
\end_inset

 if there exists a conditional density function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x_{\gamma},d,\gamma')=\int_{X}g(x_{\gamma}'\mid x)f(x_{\gamma}\mid d,\gamma)dx_{\gamma}\,\forall x_{\gamma},d
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is the sample space of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kihlstrom1974a"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After observing 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, the physician updates his prior by Bayes rule
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(s\mid x,\gamma)=f(x\mid s,\gamma)f(s,\theta)/f(x,\gamma)\label{eq:Bayes}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The change in the physicians expectation about 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 from observing the realization of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{\gamma}=x$
\end_inset

 change the expected utility.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is observed, the expected utility is now given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(t,\theta,x)=E[u(t,s,x)]=\max_{t}\int_{a}^{b}u(t,s)f(s\mid x,\gamma)ds\label{eq:updated-bayes}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
however, as the physician does not a priori know what information he receives
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

, we must average his expectation in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:updated-bayes"

\end_inset

 by the probability of all realization of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{\gamma}.$
\end_inset

 Therefore the decision about the amount of treatment 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is based on the maximization of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u(t,\theta,\gamma)=E[u(t,s,x)]=\int_{X}\max_{t}\left\{ \int_{a}^{b}u(t,s)f(s\mid x,\gamma)ds\right\} f(x,\gamma)dx\label{eq:expected-update}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:expected-update"

\end_inset

 we might similarly to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 interpret the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 to measure the degree of uncertainty about the information received.
 If the sufficiency condition holds, such that for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma<\gamma'$
\end_inset

 the information generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x'}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is a garbling of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "theorem 6.3"
key "Marschak1968"

\end_inset

 has shown that utility increases, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 decreases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Medical diagnostics and physician effort is, however, not free.
 To capture the cost of information I define the cost function 
\begin_inset Formula $C(\gamma)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is the price of observing 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{x}_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 in utiles.
 It is assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $C'(\gamma)>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C''(\gamma)>0$
\end_inset

.
